what do I need git for if there's no code..

You don’t strictly need git for YOLO training itself.

But in practice, even when there’s “no code,” git is still useful because what you’re really working with is a research artifact, not just a command.

What you actually have without git

Right now your YOLO setup likely includes:

data.yaml
dataset splits (or dataset paths)
training commands you ran
hyperparameters you tweak over time
model outputs (best.pt, runs/)
maybe small helper scripts later

That stuff changes constantly during experimentation.

Why git is still useful (even with no code)
1. Track dataset configuration changes

Example:

data.yaml

You might tweak:

class names
train/val split paths
dataset location (moving from /data1 → /data2)

Git lets you answer:

“Why did this run suddenly get worse?”

2. Track training commands + experiments

People usually keep something like:

train.sh

or:

yolo detect train model=yolo26n.pt epochs=100 imgsz=640

Then you evolve it:

change model size
change batch size
change augmentation
change dataset version

Git gives you history of experiments.

3. Save reproducibility (this is the big one)

Even if you don’t write code, you usually end up with:

project/
├── data.yaml
├── notes.md
├── train.sh
├── eval.sh

Without git:

you lose “what worked”
you overwrite configs
you forget which run produced which model

With git:

every experiment is reversible
every result is traceable
4. Collaboration (if you ever scale this)

Even on a server, eventually:

someone else wants your dataset setup
or you move jobs to another GPU box

Git becomes the transfer mechanism.

5. Versioning dataset metadata (not images)

You usually do NOT git large images, but you DO version:

data.yaml
dataset split files (train.txt, val.txt)
preprocessing scripts
labeling rules
When git is NOT useful

You can skip git if:

you're just running a one-off training job
you don’t care about reproducing results
you’re not changing configs over time

In that case:

tmux + YOLO CLI alone is enough

