Can I make a .exe file to save my env

Short answer: not in the “Windows .exe” sense on Linux.

But I think what you’re actually trying to do is one of these:

“I want to save my YOLO environment so I can reuse it without reinstalling everything.”

On Linux, you don’t use .exe files for that. You use environment snapshots or portable environments.

What you should do instead (correct approaches)
Option 1: uv environment (best for you)

You already have this set up.

To “save” your env:

uv pip freeze > requirements.txt

Then recreate it anywhere:

uv venv --python 3.12 yolo26
source yolo26/bin/activate
uv pip install -r requirements.txt

👉 This is the closest equivalent to “packing an exe”

Option 2: Copy the whole environment (not recommended)

You can try copying the folder:

cp -r ~/envs/yolo26 ~/envs/yolo26_copy

But this often breaks because:

paths are hardcoded
compiled libraries depend on system paths

So this is fragile.

Option 3: Export a fully reproducible env (best practice)

With uv:

uv pip freeze > requirements.txt

And also save Python version:

uv python list > python_version.txt

Now your “environment” becomes:

project/
├── requirements.txt
├── data.yaml
├── train.sh

This is how ML teams actually “version environments.”

Option 4: Container (closest thing to an “.exe for Linux ML”)

If you really want portability, use Docker:

docker run ...

A Docker image is basically:

“a frozen machine with your env inside”

But it requires sudo/admin on most servers, so you likely can’t use it here.

Important mental model shift

On Linux ML servers:

Windows concept	Linux ML equivalent
.exe program	script / command
installed app	Python venv
portable exe bundle	requirements.txt + uv
system snapshot	Docker image
