how do I prepare the data

Data prep is the real make-or-break step for YOLO. The model + GPU you already have are fine — what matters now is whether your dataset is in the correct structure and labels are clean.

I’ll walk you through the standard YOLO detection format (what Ultralytics expects for YOLO26).

1. What YOLO expects (core idea)

For object detection, every image needs a matching label file:

image.jpg
image.txt

The .txt file contains bounding boxes in YOLO format.

2. Correct folder structure

This is the standard:

dataset/
├── images/
│   ├── train/
│   ├── val/
│   └── test/        (optional)
├── labels/
│   ├── train/
│   ├── val/
│   └── test/
└── data.yaml
3. Label format (VERY important)

Each label file looks like this:

class_id x_center y_center width height

All values are normalized (0–1).

Example:
0 0.52 0.48 0.20 0.35
1 0.30 0.60 0.10 0.15

Meaning:

0 = class 0
box centered at (0.52, 0.48)
width = 0.20 of image width
height = 0.35 of image height
4. Your data.yaml

This tells YOLO what your dataset is:

path: /home/guest1/datasets/mydata

train: images/train
val: images/val

names:
  0: person
  1: car
  2: dog
5. How to actually prepare your data
Step A — Put images somewhere
mkdir -p ~/datasets/mydata/images/train
mkdir -p ~/datasets/mydata/images/val
Step B — Label your images

You have 3 options:

Option 1 (recommended): Roboflow / CVAT / LabelImg
LabelImg (lightweight local tool)
CVAT (powerful, web-based)
Roboflow (easy export to YOLO format)

They export directly in YOLO format.

Option 2: Manual labeling (not recommended)

You write .txt files yourself (error-prone).

Option 3: Convert existing datasets

If your data is COCO or Pascal VOC, YOLO can convert it.

6. Split dataset (train/val)

Typical split:

80% train
20% val

Example:

images/train
images/val
labels/train
labels/val

Important: images and labels must match 1:1 filenames.

7. Sanity check before training (VERY important)

Run a quick test:

yolo detect train model=yolo26n.pt data=data.yaml epochs=1

If something is wrong, YOLO will usually tell you:

missing labels
wrong paths
class mismatch
8. Common mistakes (avoid these)
❌ Wrong
labels not matching image names
forgetting normalization (values > 1)
mixing class IDs incorrectly
missing data.yaml
✅ Correct
every image has a .txt
same filename (except extension)
normalized coordinates
consistent class indexing
9. Minimal “good dataset checklist”

Before training:

 images in images/train and images/val
 labels in matching folders
 .txt files exist for every image
 data.yaml correct path
 class names defined
 run epochs=1 test
